content.description: Climb up the face untill you hit a series of cracks choose the largest and proceed up.
content.protection: Top Rope Placement is bomber on top.

content.description: Climb the broken face to the right of "Sandahl"
This is the small Dihedral on the right side of the wall.
content.location: Look for the obvious crack / Dihedral

content.description: Slightly overhanging arete (~40 feet), located between MYSTERY Climb (8th in sequence on South Wall) and Beginner's Thruch (9th in sequence in Fossum, et al guide-book). Natural arete line that begs to be climbed. Don't use ledges on Thruch. Some loose blocks seem worrisome: handle with care. Sustained angle keeps one's attention at all times. Don't know if I'm FA; no evident signs of previous climbs. Various techniques required: Jams, layback, undercling, crimps, foot-matches, side-to-side switching, and a small but essential Thank-God hold; it's all there.
content.protection: TR Recommended for G Rating; if leading, large Tri-cams & Hex-nuts on slick Sioux quartzite desired. No bolts are currently allowed at Palisades.
content.location: Arete just Right of Mystery Climb, Left of Beginner's Thruch, on attached square column on South Wall. Large tree at start of trail down from top and/or stone blocks serve as secure anchor points for TR.

content.description: Crack like face climb that isn't pretty.
crux is working feet at difficult undercling on roof
content.location: behind finger, do not use right hand arete (Laurie) or left hand crack (Dave's).

content.description: Look to the left of the dihedral for a narrow wall with tons of broken cracks.
Climb up the obvious crack system to top out.
content.protection: top rope   small cams and some stoppers should do just fine for lead climbing.

content.description: Follows the arete up to the left side of the roof. Smaller crimps lead to some arete work with limited feet.
content.protection: Probably not a lot down low
content.location: Look for a small roof on the left side of a larger break in the wall. To the east of the bottom of the stairs

content.description: Follow the face up to the right side of the small roof.  Good crimps down low, with some jams and jugs up top.Original name unknown, I'm sure someone climbed this before.
content.protection: Cracks in the top, bring some long static line to make it safe.
content.location: Just to the left of the large chimney, look up for a small roof.

content.description: Climb either of the cracks and and end at the obvious notch above you.
content.protection: Top Rope placement above is bomber.    Trad- 2 smaller cams and a few stoppers.
content.location: Look for the obvious Cave in the rock with plants growing out of it.

content.description: Nearly dead straight crack running up to the right side of the roof.  Turns into twin cracks about 30 feet up.  Finger jams, ring locks, hand cups, and a strange fist knuckle jam (idk) - Everything felt like the wrong size to fit in this crack but it's better because of that.Original name unknown, I'm sure someone has climbed this before.
content.protection: Cams, nuts.  Cracks up top, but bring some static line as some of the gear can be back a ways.
content.location: Inside left face of the large chimney.  Look for the crack that runs nearly straight up to the right side of the small roof.

climbs.name: Do You Want To Live Forever?

content.description: Start in the finger crack towards the bottom below the overhang.
we decided this route should be rated 5.8(L) to account for the crux of the route which involves pawing lichen off every hold before using it.
content.location: crack to the left of light rack club, directly behind finger

content.description: Climb up the broken Dihedral that funnels into the off width towards the top.
content.protection: top rope    small cams and stoppers for trad.

content.description: South Wall is to the left (upstream) of Harkor Tower. This wall has many fun climbs from a 5.11 to a 5.2 great wall for beginners to advanced. Top access is trivial, making top rope setups easy, while a variety of cracks allow for good trad practice. Due to the easy access and setup, South Wall is very popular. Plan to arrive early or to snag the spot as the early climbers tear down for lunch.
